# ✅ 🔶 First: Create Gold Base Table (used for ALL KPIs)

```python
from pyspark.sql import functions as F

sales = spark.read.table("electronics.silver.sales")
products = spark.read.table("electronics.silver.products")
customers = spark.read.table("electronics.silver.customers")
stores = spark.read.table("electronics.silver.stores")
exchange = spark.read.table("electronics.silver.exchange_rates")

gold_df = sales \
    .join(products, "ProductKey", "left") \
    .join(customers, "CustomerKey", "left") \
    .join(stores, "StoreKey", "left") \
    .join(exchange,
          (sales["Order Date"] == exchange["Date"]) &
          (sales["Currency Code"] == exchange["Currency"]),
          "left")

gold_df = gold_df.withColumn(
    "revenue_usd",
    F.col("Quantity") * F.col("Unit Price USD") * F.col("Exchange")
)
```

---

# ✅ 1. Monthly Revenue Trend (2024)

```python
kpi1 = gold_df.filter(F.year("Order Date") == 2024) \
    .withColumn("month", F.date_format("Order Date", "yyyy-MM")) \
    .groupBy("month") \
    .agg(F.sum("revenue_usd").alias("total_revenue")) \
    .orderBy("month")

display(kpi1)
```

---

# ✅ 2. Peak Month Analysis (Top 3 + % of annual)

```python
annual_total = kpi1.agg(F.sum("total_revenue")).collect()[0][0]

kpi2 = kpi1.orderBy(F.desc("total_revenue")).limit(3) \
    .withColumn(
        "percentage",
        (F.col("total_revenue") / F.lit(annual_total)) * 100
    )

display(kpi2)
```

---

# ✅ 3. Holiday Drivers (Top categories in peak months)

```python
top_months = [row["month"] for row in kpi2.select("month").collect()]

kpi3 = gold_df.withColumn("month", F.date_format("Order Date", "yyyy-MM")) \
    .filter(F.col("month").isin(top_months)) \
    .groupBy("month", "Category") \
    .agg(F.sum("revenue_usd").alias("revenue")) \
    .withColumn("rank", F.row_number().over(
        Window.partitionBy("month").orderBy(F.desc("revenue"))
    )) \
    .filter(F.col("rank") <= 3)

display(kpi3)
```

